    "summary": "Nabta Playa is a prehistoric site in the Nubian Desert of southern Egypt, approximately 100 kilometers west of Abu Simbel, where a large seasonal lake basin (playa) accumulated water during annual monsoon rains. During the [[event:17|African Humid Period]], this ephemeral lake attracted human communities that returned seasonally — and possibly year-round during wetter phases — leaving behind stratified archaeological deposits spanning from approximately 10,000 to 3,000 BCE.\n\nThe early phases of Nabta Playa occupation, dating to roughly 10,000–8,000 BCE, document cattle herders and hunter-gatherers exploiting the playa's water and associated plant and animal resources. The site eventually became a major ceremonial center, featuring large stone circle alignments and megalithic structures thought to have astronomical significance — making Nabta Playa possibly the world's oldest known astronomical device, predating Stonehenge by millennia. This early phase of occupation at Nabta Playa contributes to understanding the deep prehistory of the Saharan pastoral traditions that flourished during the [[event:17|Green Sahara period]] and the cultural foundations that would eventually give rise to complex societies in the Nile Valley.",
